ure, of some of the commoner animals; the use of photographs of expression submitted to different judges; and the comparative study of expression among different peoples. This new edition will be warmly welcomed by those behavioral scientists who have recently shown an intense interest in the scientific study of expression. Lay readers, too, will be struck by the freshness and directness of this book, which includes, among other data, Darwin's delightfully objective analysis of his own baby's smiles and pouts.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aEmotions. 0aInstinct. 0aPsychology, Comparative. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aemotion, cognition, cybernetics, expression, darwin, infants, insane, madness, paintings, sculpture, art, animals, photography, instinct, nonfiction, psychology, sociology, human nature, biology, zoology, suffering, weeping, anxiety, anger, grief, dejection, despair, joy, love, devotion, happiness, mental health, reflection, meditation, determination, hatred, negative, positive, blushing, shame, shyness, modesty, surprise, astonishment, horror, fear, disdain, contempt, disgust, guilt, pride, helplessness, patience, affirmation, negation.1 aLorenz, Konrad, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLorenz, Konrad.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package Archive 1960-1989z978311066784440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226220802423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226220802/original  a978-3-11-066784-4  University of Chicago Press eBook Package Archive 1960-1989c1960d1989  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles